table asyncio_extra166.asyncio_task_base_and_handle_identity:
  description: "asyncio.Task base class check and asyncio.Handle identity in asynciotbh166 namespace — asyncio.Task.__bases__[0].__name__.__eq__('Future')==True (Task.__bases__[0] is asyncio.Future; Task.__bases__[0].__name__=='Future' (len=6); Task inherits directly from Future and nothing else — single-parent inheritance; Task IS a Future (isinstance(task, asyncio.Future)==True for any task); Task adds coroutine scheduling on top of Future's state machine; Task.__bases__[0].__name__.__len__()==6 ('Future'=6; same as asyncio.Future.__name__.__len__()==6 confirmed in table above)); asyncio.Handle.__name__.__eq__('Handle')==True (asyncio.Handle is the opaque handle returned by loop.call_soon(), loop.call_later(), loop.call_at(); it wraps a callback and its arguments; Handle.__name__=='Handle' (len=6: 'H'+'a'+'n'+'d'+'l'+'e'=6; same length as 'Future'=6)); asyncio.Handle.__module__.__eq__('asyncio.events')==True (Handle is pure Python in asyncio/events.py; __module__=='asyncio.events' (len=14: 'asyncio'=7+'.'=1+'events'=6=14); 'asyncio.events'=14 > '_asyncio'=8 by 6 chars — Handle's module path is 6 chars longer than Future/Task because Handle is pure Python not C); verified with Python 3.14.3"
  kind: python_call_eq
